textAfterTable: 3 cancer screenings get Consumers Union's recommendation The Consumers Union recommended just three of 11 cancer screenings, for colon, breast and cervical cancers, in the March edition of Consumer Reports. Researchers, who based recommendations on U.S. Preventive Services Task Force data and other evidence, and said most people do not need to be tested for bladder, lung, oral, ovarian, prostate, pancreatic, skin or testicular cancers and that screening can lead to unnecessary additional testing or treatment. Medscape (free registration) (2/7)      Cases of Alzheimer's in U.S. expected to surge to 14M by 2050 Almost 14 million people could suffer from Alzheimer's disease in 2050, triple the 4.7 million seen in 2010, according to a study in the journal Neurology. The projected rise is tied to the aging of baby boomers. "This is where we're headed if we don't make any progress in Alzheimer's research," study author Jennifer Weuve said, calling efforts so far "frustrating." Nurse.com (2/6),
